I just had my wife watch the trailer and I asked her to give me an honest opinion from a non-warcraft fan who knows nothing about it. She said the movie looks like it'll be worth the money to see. text: Omfg the music. Like I don't even play wow too much any more, but the soundtrack to the Warcraft franchise from 3 onwards was one of the strongest and most key aspects. I'm sorry, but techno in the WARCRAFT trailer? Are you fucking kidding. the franchise renowned for Arthas' theme, and the opening screen orcish war drums in WoW, those masterpieces, and you're gonna use this? the whole point of Warcraft is how its theme and setting has adapted and become more complex over time; it started out as a standard point and click game from way back when, turned into the more lore focused Warcraft 3, and as wow has evolved, the lore and setting and music has become more complex and intricate, although the last couple expansions where a bit lacking. But this, this is like adding Beethoven to Call of Duty. was this decision made because gamers are stereotypically into electronic music and Warcraft is a game franchise? That's like saying alcoholics use orange juice in drinks, so all you're gonna advertise at bars is Sunny D. I'm sorry but panning over the beautifully shot Dwarven leaders, that well crafted shot really created atmosphere for me; but I lost it when you started playing fucking Skrillex. I don't even care too much about this movie, but this mistake is just so painful, like, like its fantasy, why are you using electronic music? Imagine if The Hobbit had Avicci in the trailer. It's like eating cereal with sea water.

text: Song was eh, but I kind of liked this trailer. It seems like they're really doing the WC1 "Kadghar gets a team of teenagers with attitude to stop the Horde." story, which is interesting, and I'm really liking the designs on the alliance armor in particular. Only thing that made me roll my eyes was the super easy, "Tough guy says he'll protect tough girl, she says fuck off to show how tough she is." bit.  I mean its Garona why not have her stab someone in the face to show how tough she is.   Otherwise I like the physical interplay between the actors especially; that spear toss was neat. Still not SUPER into Blizzard's weird decision to make only evil/fel touched orcs green but whatever its been nearly a decade since that ship sailed.

text: The trailers so far have been quite flashy, but I have faith that Duncan Jones and co. are saving the storytelling/world-building meat for the final product. I kinda like the song choice here (The Prodigy - The Day Is My Enemy) - as was the case with Guillermo del Toro's underrated "Pacific Rim", the makers and promoters seem appropriately tongue-in-cheek about the orc-bashes-human-bashes-orc premise. If you're going into this film with super-serious high fantasy expectations, there's a good chance for disappointment. I'm however looking forward to a rollicking popcorn extravaganza a la LotR - can't wait for the summer!

text: What I don't get is this.  Why would you take a 20+ year old franchise, with an established look, an established feel, mood, style which has been built year after year after year, forming slowly into a very well rounded world - and then as you try to make a new thing out of it, you change ALL OF THAT SHIT into something TOTALLY different - all the while ignoring the fact that you chose to make that shit in the first place because it was HUGE! And it was HUGE because of WHAT IT WAS!  I just don't get the world of entertainment sometimes. How can they so recklessly change things that WORK, for things they have no idea if they work at all? I get that they're trying to market the film for new audiences with trailers like these. But come on, if you "sell" the movie in a tone so different to what it is, what you're basically doing is lying to the customer, who will then get disappointed and shit all over your film online.  The music of warcraft MADE warcraft. Why not work with those who made it in the first place, and get them some help from some hollywood hotshot?  Where's the amazing warcraft music we're used to hear in every game trailer? It's missing so much. No trailer showed anything remotely similar to the mood of actual warcraft.  I'm sorry, but based on what we saw so far, this film is going to be a hollywood processed film. Possibly with a lot of references and some good laughs, maybe a familiar tune here and there, but the feel? Nope. That's gonna be a different feel altogether.

text: This movie started out with promise; and a lot of it.  But instead of even trying to make a a good video game movie, they're just going to turn it into a popcorn flick.  The marketing has been so unfaithful to the very concept of Warcraft, and it's unbelievable that Blizzard superfans allow them to approve this.  The CGI is so mediocre; and don't give me that "There's *SSOOOoooOoOOO* much CGI, how do you expect it all to look good?". I expect it to look good because this movie is funded by a AAA game company and Legendary Studios.  They have as much of a budget as Disney, and if you've seen the new Jungle Book, you'd know that it's not the hard to make a lot of CGI look good with the amount of money they're spending on this.    The music for the trailer was horrible.  I get it, they have to market it to a large crowd; but high-octane, orchestral battle music from Warcraft is 10x more captivating.  It's not a modern action movie, for fuck's sake.  And I'm not even going to talk about the posters.  I laughed my ass off at the sight of them.

text: I'm a fan of Warcraft and everything Blizzard (I don't play much anymore though). But let's be real. The CGI looks lowkey ASS. And it's kind of disrespectful to the fans imo if you really look at it. Activision-Blizzard is one of the most popular game companies that is worth 20 billion dollars today. This company probably has the most loyal  consumers as well. I mean all their stuff is great imo, But you can't deny the fact that they do some ho shit. For example, having a subscription for world of Warcraft for so long when other mmos that were more detailed and dynamic didn't... Not selling heroes of the storm as a full game but making you buy the characters individually which adds up to more than $100 and they are still adding more (or you can grind a century and a half to get them)... Overwatch for $60 when fps-wise its kind of below average in graphic in detail but I bet gameplay is great. And oh boy on the Activision side... Rehash after rehash of cod after cod. They release DLC and do micro-transactions that are nothing but vanity and don't improve gameplay.   SO WITH ALL THAT SAID... I THINK THE LEAST THEY CAN DO IS FUND THE MOVIE MORE OR SOME SHIT FOR BETTER CGI. BUT NOPE IT SEEMS THEY ARE GOING TO RELY ON THEIR FANS WHO ARE ACCUSTOMED TO SETTLING. THE HUNTSMAN WHICH CAME OUT THIS WEEKEND HAD A BUDGET OF 170 MILLION AND THEY USED IT WELL. EXCELLENT CGI AND CHOREOGRAPHY. WARCRAFT MOVIE HAD A BUDGET OF 100 MILLION. AND FROM THE TRAILERS I CAN SEE THE DIFFERENCE OF 70 MILLION ALREADY. AND IT'S CRAZY BECAUSE WARCRAFT IS WHAT GOT BLIZZARD WHERE IT IS TODAY. SMH

text: This trailer really shows just how blind the corporate side of the project is to both fans of the game and gamers in general.  They must have went by corporate statistics that they bought from "official" sources instead of just listening to some sort of experienced adviser and generalized fans of Warcraft with "all the other gamers".  The reason I put those words in quotations was because that the statistics they found probably labeled all gamers as fans of dubstep, when the reality is that first-person shooters still have a following larger than their own good.  Hence, the reason why a lot of gamers would even still enjoy dubstep.  In fact, the marketing department doesn't even seem to know too much past the generalized statistical-based research because they have not considered how the fan base for generic first person shooters is large and casual to the point where they are actually pretty distant from the flip side (or true side, in my perspective) of the gamer community.

text: I'm glad they played something other than the traditional choice of "epic orchestra music" for this trailer. The Prodigy was a fine choice, maybe not the best but objectively it sounded suitable for this trailer. Fantasy as a genre has the potential to grow when it breaks/challenges the norms it so often adheres to. It'll only stagnant and become dull if it constantly conforms to the expectations of a narrow definition. Hell, where would Fantasy Orcs be if Warcraft didn't eventually develop them away from being purely a mindless horde? I'm excited for this movie and if one or two trailers are going to steer you away from seeing it then shit I guess I'll have a better pick of the seats when it comes out.

text: I dearly hope that music isn't part of the film's soundtrack. There's already a sizable library of established music to draw on, and neglecting all of that source material is perplexing. Star Wars could have used contemporary music (read: Disco), but the decision to go with an orchestral score made the experience much more palatable, especially for future audiences-- assuming the big guys in production even intend for this film to become something people watch years from now in the first place. Metzen and the rest of Blizzard are hoping this will be the case, but I'm skeptical about Legendary's endgame. I'm going to remain cautiously optimistic: walk into the theater hoping for Lord of the Rings but expecting The Hobbit.

text: I just watched it and this is my personal rating, The movie is a fucking 5/5!!  disclaimer: I'm a bit biased because I'm a fan of the Warcraft games in general especially the RTS. Warcraft 1 was one of my first RTS that I played along with C&C and that's way back in 1995. Anyway I'll just list the it's pros and cons of the movie.  Pros: + They nailed the look of the movie, especially the ORCs. It just looks and feels like Warcraft. + CGI is amazing, definitely one of the best by ILM. The facial expressions of the Orcs are just awesome to look at, it might rival Avatar in that department. +  The  ingame locations, stormwind, dalaran. Seeing it in the big screen is a joy to us Warcraft fans. (Although some locations are not accurate like Dalaran is not supposed to float not until Archimonde sieged it during the events of WC3) + Dialogue is good enough, dont expect some LotR narrative. + Lothar is just awesome, hopefully we will see more of Travis Fimmel in the big screen.Overall most of the actors did well even the CGI orcs Durotan, Ogrim,  Guldan etc. + It's action packed no dull moments for me. + Magics are represented well in this movie, theres incantations and  magic circle.  If you are a mage in World of Warcraft you prolly had  orgasmed after seeing it lol. + There are some shots later on when the cameras are overhead and it looked like a warcraft RTS game. + This movie gave me feels than that specific BvS scene.    Cons - Some plotpoints might be confusing because the movie is just only 2HRs, the movie pacing is quite fast. - Not adding some familiar game music is a missed opportunity.  - Dwarves are CGI - Battles are quite short I expected more :D  The movie ending is open for a sequel, there's a few surprises don't expect that this movie will have a fairy tale ending.  I think the movie will hold itself well to those who are not familiar with the source material. I just hope that the movie will do well in the box office, it needs its returns for future sequel/s. The Warcraft lore is just vast and it will be a shame if this first movie will be the last. Just go ahead have an open mind and watch it, Ignore the critics. Your opinion is what matter most. The movie entertained me than most recent superhero movie releases. Hopefully the Assassins creed movie will do well, we need more good videogame movies.

I mean I left the cinema liking Ben Schnetzer (Khadgar) when I was worried about him the most!, Travis Fimmel was pathetically bland, Paula Patton just bored me, Dominic Cooper was completely miss-cast, and Ryan Robbins was underused. I REALLY hope that this film gets a sequel with a better director (Sorry, Duncan, you seem nice but I can't blame anyone else), better fight choreographers, and less lore changes to fit the film's plot.

author: Blue Phoenix Entertainment

text: I just saw the movie and in my honest opinion, I loved every single minute of it. I've played wow for 6-7 years on and off, and watching this movie has peaked my interest in the game...again. I've realized that wow is more than just gameplay; it's also enjoying the lore! Wow gets boring if all you do is level>gear up>raid or high rating pvp. Not to say that none of those things are fun, but actually knowing what's going on, like the story behind the quests makes things more interesting! Did you know King Varian named his son, Anduin, after Lothar in this movie? It's interesting! Everyone is connected, and it's like one big puzzle. Your toon adds to Warcraft history. With that in mind, I'll continue my adventures in Azeroth, forever protecting my fellow Alliance(and some Horde). For Azeroth!
